{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1097.erdos_1097 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1097.erdos_1097.","id":"vf_8c6a4b6ebead3678","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: Slight improvement to past construction.","id":"vf_a99786894a141d1f","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1097: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $A$ be a set of $n$ integers. How many distinct $d$ can occur as the common difference of a three-term arithmetic progression in $A$? Are there always $O(n^{3/2})$ many such $d$? Current best: He states that Erd\\H{o}s and Ruzsa gave an explicit construction which achieved $n^{1+c}$ for some $c>0$, and Erd\\H{o}s and Spencer gave a probabilistic proof which achieved $n^{3/2}$, and speculated this may be the best possible. The current best bounds known are thus\\[1.77898\\cdots \\leq c \\leq 11/6 \\approx 1.833.\\]The upper bound is due to Katz and Tao \\cite{KaTa99}. The lower bound is due to Lemm \\cite{Le15} (with a very small improvement found by AlphaEvolve \\cite{GGTW25}). Prize: no. Tags: additive combinatorics, number theory.","id":"vf_b3fc76429d25e6a3","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/1097.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_8c6a4b6ebead3678","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:1097","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_8c6a4b6ebead3678","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b